First, make sure you've installed Discord.js v14 in your project. You can do this by running `npm install discord.js@14`.

Here's an example of how to create a basic Discord bot with one command using Discord.js v14 and Node.js.

1. Create a new JavaScript file (e.g., `ban.js`) in your project's root directory.

2. Inside the `ban.js` file, add the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents } = require('discord.js');

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMessages] });

// Register the command
client.on('commandRegex', async (cmd, message) => {
    if (cmd.command === 'ban') {
        const args = message.content.slice(1).split(/ +/);

        if (args.length < 3) {
            return message.reply('Usage: `!ban <user> <reason>`.');
        }

        // Fetch or update the user's ban
        const user = message.member;
        const serverID = message.guild.id;

        // Replace 'reason' with your preferred ban reason
        let banReason = args.slice(2).join(' ');

        try {
            await client.ban(user.id, { reason: banReason, time: 777600000 }).then(async () => {
                await message.channel.send(`Successfully banned ${user.tag} from the server with reason: ${banReason}`);
            });
        } catch (error) {
            console.error(error);
            return message.channel.send('Error:', { embed: { color: 'red' } });
        }
    }
});

client.login('your_bot_token');
```

Replace `'your_bot_token'` with your actual bot token provided by the Discord Developer Portal.

3. To run your bot, open a terminal in your project's root directory, and execute:

```bash
node ban.js
```

This will start the bot. To test your command, use a slash command format like this:

```
!ban <user> <reason>
```

For example, to ban user123 for 1 year (777600000 milliseconds = 1 year):
```
!ban user123 "This user has been banned for a year."
```

Remember you need to register the bot and get an invite link from the Discord Developer Portal before running the bot.

This is a basic example. You can further customize the bot by handling errors, adding more commands, and managing users' permissions.

Here's a simple C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing html formatted text. This function uses the `mmarkdown` library to parse the markdown text and convert it to html.
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>
#include <mmarkdown.hpp>
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Initialize the Markdown parser
    mmarkdown::document doc;
    doc.parse(markdown);
    // Convert the Markdown document to HTML
    std::stringstream htmlStream;
    htmlStream << doc.toString();
    return htmlStream.str();
}
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "[Hello](https://example.com)"
                             "World! [1](https://example.com) [2](https://example.com)";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
You can compile and run this code on your system. In this example, the `markdownToHtml` function takes a `std::string` containing markdown text as an argument. The function initializes a `mmarkdown::document` object and parses the markdown text using the `parse` method. Then, it converts the parsed document to html by using the `toString()` method and writes the resulting html text to a `std::stringstream`.
In the `main` function, we create a markdown string and pass it to the `markdownToHtml` function. The function returns the html string, which is then printed to the console.
Please note that you'll need to include the `mmmarkdown.hpp` header file and link against the `mmmarkdown` library to use this code. You can install the `mmmarkdown` library using the following command:
```
pip install mmmarkdown
```
You can also find more information about this library and how to use it in the [mmmarkdown documentation](https://docs.marmotmarkdown.com/latest/userguide/html.html)
It's worth mentioning that there are other libraries available for markdown to html conversion like [Pandoc](https://pandoc.org/), [Markdown.js](https://markdownjs.com/), and [Jekyll](https://jekyllrb.com/)
